ACTION:
{"action": "event", "reason": "Captain Reva examined the cargo of the last ship to dock, noticing the sealed black glass jars with faintly glowing markings.", "target": "captain_reva", "event": "Captain Reva took a closer look at the crates of the last ship to dock, noting the sealed black glass jars with faintly glowing markings. She frowned, her hands trembling as she recalled the lighthouse keeper's disappearance and the dark lighthouse. She decided to have her dock workers search the crates for any signs of smuggling tunnels."}

No more than one of these options per tick.

ACTION:
{"action": "event", "reason": "Gen T14 Bryn Oakshield noticed a shadowy figure lingering near the docks, examining the crates and barrels with a worried expression.", "target": "gen_t14_bryn_oakenshield", "event": "Gen T14 Bryn Oakshield noticed a shadowy figure lingering near the docks, examining the crates and barrels with a worried expression, and his hands trembled as he watched the figure."}

Do not describe the same NPC from a different perspective.

ACTION:
{"action": "event", "reason": "Gen T14 Bryn Oakshield notices a shadowy figure lingering near the docks again.", "target": "gen_t14_bryn_oakenshield", "event": "Gen T14 Bryn Oakshield observed a shadowy figure moving slowly near the docks, casting long shadows in the moonlight, and whispered to himself, 'That hooded figure is back. What's going on here?'"}

For example, instead of saying "Nils Larkspur saw the figure and followed it", you might say "Nils Larkspur saw a shadowy figure near the docks and thought it might be a smuggler. He decided to keep a closer eye on the figure." This way, the new fact is consistent with the previous one, but adds a new detail to the story.

ACTION:

{"action": "event", "reason": "Nils Larkspur notices a shadowy figure near the docks again, this time he decides to investigate.", "target": "gen_t19_nils_larkspur", "event": "Nils Larkspur noticed a shadowy figure near the docks at night. He thought it might be a smuggler and decided to follow the figure, keeping a sharp eye on its movements."}
